  "prompt": "Why do weights of assets in a portfolio turn negative when I short sell that asset?",
  "response": "When you short sell an asset, the weight of that asset in the portfolio becomes negative. This is because:\n\n1. In short selling, you borrow shares and sell them, expecting to buy them back later at a lower price\n\n2. A negative weight represents a short position in the portfolio\n\n3. Instead of owning the asset (positive weight), you are effectively \"negative\" in that asset\n\nFor example:\n- If you have a $100 portfolio and short $20 of a stock, that stock's weight would be -20%\n- This means you've bet against that asset's performance\n- A negative weight indicates you'll profit if the asset's price falls\n\nThe negative weight mathematically reflects that you've sold borrowed shares, creating an obligation to repurchase them, which is different from a traditional long position.\n\nMathematically, portfolio weights must still sum to 100%, so short positions reduce the positive weights of other assets accordingly.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any part of this explanation?",
